PROJECT BACKGROUND AND DESCRIPTION
Project Objective
To reduce NRW from 67% to 25% by 2028 in compliance with sector standard. This is to align with the outputs of the National NRW Strategy and the NRW strategy of the utility company.
Status Before Project
Luapula Water Supply and Sanitation Company’s Non-Revenue Water is averaged at 67% currently and this has caused inefficient and unreliable supply of water. In turn this has caused low revenue collection as we only collect on the 33% of water from the 100% produced and supplied. Due to lack of software that integrates the meters and the billing system this has caused data handling errors and inefficient billing.
LpWSC currently has the highest NRW in the sector of 67%. This has not only negatively affected the profitability of the business, but also failing to extend service provision due to high physical losses.
Status After Project
Luapula Water Supply and Sanitation Company Limited (LpWSC) will be able to supply water to all connected customers efficiently as the NRW levels will be at the accepted standard of 25% by NWASCO and further below. This in turn will cause the revenue levels to also increase as 75% of water produced will be accounted for. Due to the project, integrating softwares between the much needed Electromagnetic water meters, complete with GPRS loggers and the billing system will be available, this will reduce data handling errors, make billing efficient and having up to date information on customers.
The project aligns with National Vision 2030, Sustainable development goal N0 6, and the Zambian Government’s 8th National Development Plan.
Justification
In order to meet the mandate of ensuring that Non-Revenue Water (NRW) for Luapula Water Supply and Sanitation Company Limited (LpWSC) is at the acceptable standard by NWASCO of 25% and below, with this efficiency, (LpWSC) can have the operational funding it needs to achieve its goals and vision.
To improve the profitability of the utility company, improve service provision, and meet the sector standard for NRW
Options analysis and Technical Feasibility
To ensure timely delivery of the project, it is hereby proposed that the project is split into two phases. Phase 1 should consist of 4 District Metered Areas (DMAs). 2 DMAs to be selected in Mansa and 2 in Samfya. And phase 2 will include all DMAs in the districts. The proposed layout of the technical requirements are laid out in appendix 1 and BOQs for technical requirements in appendix 2
