OUTPUTS
1. Reduction in Water Losses
 Physical losses (leaks, pipe bursts) will be significantly reduced, improving the overall efficiency of the water distribution system.
 Commercial losses (illegal connections, meter inaccuracies, billing errors) will also be minimized through better monitoring and control.
2. Increased Water Supply Availability
 More water will be available to customers without increasing production, improving access to water, especially during peak demand periods or in water-scarce areas.
3. Enhanced Revenue Generation
 With more water being billed and less lost, the utility will experience a direct increase in revenue, improving financial sustainability.
 This also reduces dependency on government subsidies or external funding.
4. Improved Operational Efficiency
 Optimized water usage leads to lower energy and chemical costs for water treatment and pumping, enhancing cost-efficiency.
 Maintenance will become more proactive, focusing on preventive
