5. Extended Lifespan of Infrastructure
 Reducing leaks and pressure surges in the system extends the life of pipes, pumps, and other infrastructure, lowering long-term capital expenditure on repairs and replacements.
6. Better Water Quality
 Improved control over the distribution system reduces contamination risks from leaks, ensuring a safer and cleaner water supply for customers.
7. More Accurate Data for Planning
 Upgraded metering, leak detection technologies, and system monitoring will provide the utility with more accurate data, enabling better long-term planning and decision-making.
8. Improved Customer Satisfaction
 With fewer interruptions, better service reliability, and improved water quality, customer satisfaction is expected to increase. This may also lead to improved public trust and cooperation with the utility.
9. Reduction in Water Production Costs
 As less water is lost, the need for excessive production will decrease, resulting in cost savings related to pumping, treating, and distributing water.
10. Environmental Sustainability
 Reducing NRW will conserve valuable water resources, helping to mitigate the impact on local ecosystems and contributing to environmental sustainability.
 It will also reduce the energy footprint associated with water treatment and distribution, lowering the utility’s overall environmental impact.
11. Strengthened Capacity and Skills
 The project will likely involve the adoption of modern technologies (like advanced metering infrastructure and smart leak detection systems), which can enhance the technical capacity of staff and improve organizational competency.
12. Improved Public Health Outcomes
 A more reliable, continuous supply of clean water reduces the risk of waterborne diseases, which directly improves community health outcomes.
13. Regulatory Compliance and Improved Reputation
 Achieving NRW reduction targets can demonstrate compliance with regulatory standards, improving the utility’s standing with government bodies, investors, and customers.
14. Cost Stabilization for Customers
 By improving efficiency and reducing operational losses, the utility may be able to avoid sharp increases in water tariffs, providing more stable and affordable water pricing for consumers.
